full_text:
I've been reading Seth Klarman’s Margin of Safety.

In a 2012 letter, Klarman said he “endeavoured to make the book timeless - more about how to think about investing than about what one should buy or sell at any given moment”.

15 takeaways so far:

https://t.co/WSJ6Hs6cVF
name: CMac

full_text: 1/ Trading Sardines, the origin story\n\n"He immediately became ill and told the seller the sardines were no good. The seller said, "You don't understand. These are not eating sardines, they are trading sardines”. https://t.co/duKTHAuGRS
name: CMac

full_text: 2/ Not all selloffs are buying opportunities\n\n"Investors would be much better off to redirect the time and effort committed to devising formulas into fundamental analysis of specific investment opportunities”. https://t.co/fwWphj0he0
name: CMac

full_text: 3/ Mr Market is an avenue for investment guidance and feedback loops for some and a vehicle of opportunity for others. https://t.co/nNX4lSJgDv
name: CMac

full_text: 4/ Business reality vs. Stock price\n\n"Value in relation to price, not price alone, must determine your investment decisions". https://t.co/EmYXqE7BL7
name: CMac

full_text: 5/ Stock prices move for 2 reasons, changes in perceived reality and shifts in supply and demand. https://t.co/J5JPfpf1EW
name: CMac

full_text: 6/ Avoiding loss is rule number one\n\n"While no one wishes to incur losses, you couldn't prove it from an examination of the behaviour of most investors and speculators". https://t.co/YIExDotjmf
name: CMac

full_text: 7/ The folly of targetting investment returns\n\n"Investment returns are not a direct function of how long or hard you work or how much you wish to earn. A ditch digger can work an hour of overtime for extra pay, and a piece worker earns more the more he or she produces". https://t.co/ZHsHKo9zCN
name: CMac

full_text: 8/ Volatility ≠ Risk\n\n"While investors should obviously try to avoid overpaying for investments or buying into businesses that subsequently decline in value due to deteriorating results, it is not possible to avoid random short-term market volatility". https://t.co/WcY3DnYvPI
name: CMac

full_text: 9/ When price fluctuation matters https://t.co/IOA2b58xW9
name: CMac

full_text: 12/ Expecting precision in an imprecise world https://t.co/lrmamJCg7E
name: CMac

full_text: 13/ Investing vs. Speculation https://t.co/fbD6hmqfks
name: CMac

And they're off! The gates fly open, and it's a strong start from the entire field. Steve is quick out of the gate, immediately grabbing the early lead, with Adam just a half-length behind. John is right there too, settling comfortably into third as they charge down the opening straight. 

Further back, we have Greg and Paul running side by side in fourth and fifth. Mike is hanging back a bit in sixth, conserving his energy for later, while Dave, Mark, and Chris are biding their time at the rear of the pack. 

As they approach the first turn, Steve continues to hold the lead, but Adam is not letting him out of his sight. John remains in third, and now we see Greg starting to edge ahead of Paul into fourth. Mike is still lurking in the middle, just waiting for the right moment. Chris, meanwhile, is starting to pick up the pace, moving up on the outside past Mark and Dave, who are content to trail the field for now. 

They're into the backstretch now, and here comes the first big move! John is making a play for the lead, pulling up alongside Steve! Steve is fighting to maintain his position, but John is relentless, and it looks like he might just edge ahead! Meanwhile, Adam is sticking right with them, not willing to let either of them out of his sight. 

Back in the pack, Greg is still holding onto fourth, but now Mike is making a move! Mike is gaining ground rapidly, cutting down the distance between himself and the leaders. Chris isn't far behind, and it looks like Paul is also starting to make his move. Mark and Dave are still at the back, but they're beginning to inch closer, not wanting to be left out of the action. 

As they approach the final turn, it's still Steve and John battling it out at the front, but Adam is right there with them, and now Mike is joining the fray! Greg is trying to hang on, but Chris is charging hard on the outside! Paul is digging deep, trying to stay in contention, while Mark and Dave are finally starting to come alive, making their move from the back of the pack. 

Here they come into the home stretch! It's a four-horse race now, with Steve, John, Adam, and Mike all neck and neck! Greg is giving it everything he has to stay with them, but Chris is flying down the outside! Paul is trying to stay in touch, and now Mark and Dave are absolutely motoring from the back—what a finish this is going to be! 

It's Steve! No, it's John! But wait, here comes Mike with a huge burst of speed! Adam is right there too, and Chris is not far behind! They’re all flying towards the finish line, it’s anyone's race now! 

Steve and John are still battling it out, but Mike is closing fast, and now Adam is finding something extra! Chris is still coming on strong, and here comes Mark out of nowhere with a late surge! Dave is also flying down the track—unbelievable scenes here as they approach the line!

And it's... it's... it's JOHN! John just edges it out in a stunning finish! Steve and Mike are right there, almost too close to call for second! Adam finishes a strong fourth, followed by Chris, Greg, and Mark, with Dave and Paul just behind them! What a race! What a finish! John takes it by the narrowest of margins!
